<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-tools" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Software Tools</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      This appendix gives a brief introduction to the software packages required
      for working with R Markdown and <c>bookdown</c>, with an emphasis on how
      to install and maintain the core tools.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="r-and-r-packages">
    <title>R and R packages</title>

    <p>
      R can be downloaded from a CRAN mirror such as
      <url href="https://cran.rstudio.com" visual="cran.rstudio.com"/>. Since R
      has several releases each year, the chapter notes that you may want to
      upgrade it occasionally.
    </p>

    <p>
      To install <c>bookdown</c>, the Rmd source first gives the simplest
      package-installation command.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>install.packages("bookdown")</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      It then shows how to install optional dependencies as well, which can be
      convenient if you do not mind installing packages that may not be used in
      a given project.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>install.packages("bookdown", dependencies = TRUE)</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      To test the development version from GitHub, the chapter recommends
      installing <c>devtools</c> first if necessary and then installing
      <c>bookdown</c> from the repository.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>if (!requireNamespace('devtools')) install.packages('devtools')
devtools::install_github('rstudio/bookdown')</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      Since packages on CRAN and GitHub are updated regularly, the chapter also
      suggests updating your installed packages from time to time.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>update.packages(ask = FALSE)</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      Although it is not required, the chapter also recommends the RStudio IDE
      as a convenient environment for R-related work. The RStudio IDE can be
      downloaded from <url href="https://www.posit.co"
      visual="posit.co"/>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="pandoc">
    <title>Pandoc</title>

    <p>
      The chapter explains that an <c>*.Rmd</c> file is first compiled to
      Markdown through <c>knitr</c>, then converted to formats such as HTML or
      LaTeX through Pandoc, with <c>rmarkdown</c> automating that workflow.
    </p>

    <p>
      Because <c>knitr</c> and <c>rmarkdown</c> are required by <c>bookdown</c>,
      they are installed automatically with the package. Pandoc is different:
      it is not an R package, so it must be installed separately unless you are
      using the copy bundled with the RStudio IDE.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Rmd chapter shows how to query the Pandoc version available to
      <c>rmarkdown</c>.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>rmarkdown::pandoc_version()</input>
      <output>[1] '1.19.2.1'</output>
    </program>

    <p>
      If that version is too old for a needed feature, the chapter notes that a
      newer system installation of Pandoc can override the bundled version.
    </p>

    <p>
      Readers can follow the installation instructions on the Pandoc homepage
      (<url href="http://pandoc.org" visual="pandoc.org"/>) if they need to
      install Pandoc separately.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="latex">
    <title>LaTeX</title>

    <p>
      LaTeX is only required when you want PDF output. The chapter strongly
      recommends the lightweight, cross-platform TinyTeX distribution based on
      TeX Live, which can be installed through the <c>tinytex</c> R package.
    </p>

    <p>
      It also points readers to <url href="https://www.latex-project.org/get/"
      visual="latex-project.org/get"/> for more information about LaTeX
      distributions and installation.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>tinytex::install_tinytex()</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The Rmd source includes the following verbatim error output to show the
      kind of missing-package failure that TinyTeX can help avoid.
    </p>

    <program language="latex-error">
      <input>! LaTeX Error: File `titling.sty' not found.

Type X to quit or &lt;RETURN&gt; to proceed,
or enter new name. (Default extension: sty)

Enter file name:
! Emergency stop.
&lt;read *&gt;

l.107 ^^M

pandoc: Error producing PDF
Error: pandoc document conversion failed with error 43
Execution halted</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter explains that this error means a required LaTeX package was
      missing. With TinyTeX and R Markdown, such missing packages are installed
      automatically, so readers generally do not need to resolve them by hand.
    </p>

    <p>
      It also notes that LaTeX package names are often the same as the
      <c>*.sty</c> filenames, so in this case you could try to install the
      <c>titling</c> package directly.
    </p>

    <p>
      It also shows how to inspect the installed LaTeX version from R. The first
      snippet captures <c>pdflatex --version</c> and reformats the result so it
      can be inserted back into the rendered document as display text.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>res &lt;- base::system('pdflatex --version', intern = TRUE)
res &lt;- paste("## ", res)
res &lt;- paste0(res, collapse = "\n")</input>
      <output>## pdfTeX 3.141592653-2.6-1.40.24 (TeX Live 2022)
## kpathsea version 6.3.4
## Copyright 2022 Han The Thanh</output>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>system('pdflatex --version')</input>
      <output>## pdfTeX 3.141592653-2.6-1.40.24 (TeX Live 2022)
## kpathsea version 6.3.4
## Copyright 2022 Han The Thanh</output>
    </program>

    <p>
      For maintenance, the chapter recommends updating TinyTeX packages when you
      run into LaTeX problems and reinstalling TinyTeX entirely if an annual
      upgrade becomes necessary.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>tinytex::tlmgr_update()</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>tinytex::reinstall_tinytex()</input>
    </program>
  </section>
</chapter>
